That failure mode is plausible if the mutex lives in the wrong lifecycle/scope.

A mutex only prevents duplicate refresh work among callers that share the same mutex object. If each request handler, route module instance, worker, tenant context, or service class instance creates its own mutex, then concurrent requests for the same tenant can acquire different locks and still race.

Typical problematic shapes:

```ts
class AuthHandler {
  private refreshMutex = new Mutex()

  async handle(req) {
    // only protects concurrency inside this one handler instance
  }
}
```

or:

```ts
function createHandler() {
  const refreshMutex = new Mutex()

  return async function handle(req) {
    // new handler factory call means a new lock
  }
}
```

It also serializes too much if the critical section wraps the whole request path instead of only the refresh decision/install step:

```ts
await mutex.runExclusive(async () => {
  validateRequest()
  callDownstream()
  maybeRefreshToken()
  buildResponse()
})
```

That would make unrelated work wait behind token refresh logic, increasing latency and creating head-of-line blocking.

The lock needs to be scoped to the shared contention key, likely tenant/session/client credential, and shared across all code paths that can refresh that same token:

```ts
const locksByTenant = new Map<string, Mutex>()
```

Even then, in a multi-process or multi-node service, an in-memory mutex only protects one process. If duplicate refreshes across workers matter, the coordination must move to a shared store or use an atomic compare-and-set / lease mechanism.
